  "local_port": 43392,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "My driving license is lost. How do I apply for a new one?",
  "response": "I'm sorry to hear that you've lost your driving license. Replacing a lost license involves a few standard steps, though the exact process can vary depending on your country or region. Below is a general guide to help you get started:\n\n### **1. Determine Where to Apply**\n- **Identify the Relevant Authority:** Typically, driving licenses are managed by a governmental department such as the Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV) in the United States, the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) in the United Kingdom, or equivalent agencies in other countries.\n\n### **2. Gather Necessary Information and Documents**\nYou will generally need the following:\n- **Personal Identification:** Such as a passport, birth certificate, or national ID.\n- **Proof of Residency:** Utility bills, lease agreements, or other documents that verify your current address.\n- **Social Security Number (if applicable):** In some countries like the U.S., this may be required.\n- **Driver's License Number:** If you have any documentation that includes your previous license number, it can be helpful.\n\n### **3. Complete the Application Form**\n- **Online Application:** Many regions offer online services for replacing lost licenses. Visit the official website of your local licensing authority to check availability.\n- **In-Person Application:** If online services aren't available or if you prefer handling it in person, you can visit a local office. It might be necessary to make an appointment beforehand.\n- **Mail-In Application:** Some authorities allow you to mail in your application. Ensure you use the correct forms and include all required documentation.\n\n### **4. Pay the Replacement Fee**\n- **Fees Vary:** The cost can range from modest to moderately priced, depending on your location.\n- **Payment Methods:** Online applications typically accept credit/debit cards, while in-person or mail-in applications might require checks or money orders.\n\n### **5. Submit Your Application**\n- **Online Submission:** Follow the prompts on the official website.\n- **In-Person Submission:** Bring all required documents and payment to the licensing office.\n- **Mail Submission:** Send your completed form and supporting documents to the address specified by the licensing authority.\n\n### **6. Receive Your Replacement License**\n- **Processing Time:** This can range from immediate (if issued in person) to several weeks (if mailed).\n- **Temporary License:** Some regions provide a temporary license or receipt that serves as proof until your replacement arrives.\n\n### **Additional Tips:**\n- **Report the Loss:** If you suspect your license was stolen, consider reporting it to local law enforcement to prevent potential identity theft.\n- **Check for Updates:** Ensure that your address and other personal information are up to date to avoid delays.\n- **Renewal:** If your license was close to expiring, you might be able to renew it simultaneously.\n\n### **Country-Specific Guidelines:**\n\n#### **United States:**\n- Visit your state's DMV website (e.g., [California DMV](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/)).\n- Most states offer online replacement services.\n- Identification requirements and fees vary by state.\n\n#### **United Kingdom:**\n- Apply online through the [DVLA website](https://www.gov.uk/replace-driving-licence).\n- Alternatively, complete a D1 form available at most post offices.\n- Provide a new passport-style photo if required.\n\n#### **Canada:**\n- Procedures vary by province. For example:\n  - **Ontario:** Use ServiceOntario online or visit a ServiceOntario center.\n  - **British Columbia:** Apply through ICBC (Insurance Corporation of British Columbia).\n\n#### **Australia:**\n- Application processes differ by state:\n  - **New South Wales:** Apply online via Service NSW.\n  - **Victoria:** Use VicRoads online services or visit a VicRoads office.\n\n### **Final Recommendation:**\nSince procedures can vary significantly based on your location, it's best to visit the official website of your local motor vehicle or licensing authority. They will provide the most accurate and detailed instructions tailored to your specific situation.\n\nIf you let me know your country or region, I can offer more targeted information!",
